          "body": "Verses 14-18 are the chapter's climax. Because the children share *flesh and blood* (the standard Jewish idiom for ordinary human existence), the Son *partook of the same* — real incarnation, not docetic appearance. The purpose is two-edged: to *render powerless* (*katargeō*) the one who held the power of death (the devil) and to *free* (*apallassō*) those held in lifelong slavery by fear of death. The chapter ends with the letter's first use of *archiereus* (high priest), qualified by two adjectives that set the agenda for chapters 3–10: *merciful* (toward His brethren who suffer and sin) and *faithful* (toward the God to whom He offers Himself). *Hilaskomai* (v. 17) is propitiation — the satisfying of righteous wrath against sin, not the mere covering of it. The chapter closes (v. 18) with the pastoral payoff: because He Himself suffered when tempted, He is able to come running to the aid of those being tempted."
