        "number": 2,
        "title": "Psalm 8 fulfilled — but we do see Jesus",
        "range": "2:5-9",
        "excerpt": "But we do see Him who was made for a little while lower than the angels, namely, Jesus, because of the suffering of death crowned with glory and honor.",
        "body": "Verse 5 connects the warning to the exposition with a *gar* (for): God has not subjected the world to come to angels. The phrase *tēn oikoumenēn tēn mellousan* — *the inhabited world to come* — is the eschatological *renewed creation* over which Christ reigns and into which He is bringing the many sons. The dignity of that rule belongs to humanity by creation and is fulfilled in the Son of Man — not in angelic powers, however exalted. This subtly answers any Jewish-Christian tendency to overvalue angelic mediators (a temptation the audience evidently faced; cf. Colossians 2:18).\n\nVerses 6-8a quote Psalm 8:4-6 LXX. The author's vague *one has testified somewhere* (*pou*) is not ignorance of authorship — it is a rhetorical convention common in rabbinic and Hellenistic writing that emphasizes the divine source over the human author. The psalm itself meditates on Genesis 1:26-28: humanity, though small in the cosmos, is crowned with glory and honor and given dominion over creation. The author quotes the psalm and then makes a critical observation: *in subjecting all things to him, He left nothing that is not subject to him. But now we do not yet see all things subjected to him* (v. 8b). This is the chapter's most candid acknowledgment of the present condition. The Edenic mandate was lost in the fall; fallen humanity does not look like the kingly creature of Psalm 8.\n\nVerse 9 is the chapter's hinge: *but we do see Jesus*. The contrast *blepomen* (we see) bears the entire eschatological tension. We do *not* see all things subjected to humanity, but we *do* see Jesus — the Last Adam — already crowned with glory and honor *because of the suffering of death* (*dia to pathēma tou thanatou*). The instrumental phrase is critical: He is crowned not despite the cross but *because of* it. Suffering and glory are not alternatives in Hebrews; they are sequence.\n\nThe phrase *so that by the grace of God He might taste death for everyone* states the cross's purpose. *Geuomai* (taste) is Semitic idiom for the full experience of a thing (cf. Mark 9:1; John 8:52). Christ did not sample death; He drank its bitterness fully. *By the grace of God* (*chariti theou*) reminds the reader that the cross is not a tragedy God reluctantly permitted but a gift He sovereignly gave. The scope *hyper pantos* — *for every one* — has occasioned debate; the orthodox consensus is that the atonement is sufficient for all without exception and efficient for those who are united to Christ by faith. Hebrews does not flatten either side: the universal sufficiency is real, and the chapter's particularizing language (*many sons*, *brethren*, *seed of Abraham*, *the people*) marks the efficient scope.\n\nThe Christological reading of Psalm 8 has occasionally been challenged by interpreters who insist the psalm refers only to generic humanity. The author of Hebrews does not deny that — he affirms it (v. 8a) — but he insists that the psalm's promise is fulfilled first and decisively in Jesus the representative man, the Last Adam (1 Corinthians 15:45), and through Him in the *many sons*.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Brachy ti* (a little while) is grammatically temporal in Hebrews 2:7, 9 (not 'a little lower' in degree, as some translations imply, but 'lower for a little while'). *Elattoō* (made lower) reappears at v. 9 — same verb, same subject of the verb? No: same verb, two referents (generic man in v. 7; Jesus the representative man in v. 9). *Pathēma* (suffering) is concrete — what was endured — not abstract pain."
