        "title": "Pioneer of salvation, perfected through sufferings",
        "range": "2:10-13",
        "excerpt": "For it was fitting for Him… in bringing many sons to glory, to perfect the author of their salvation through sufferings.",
        "body": "Verse 10 is the theological capstone of the chapter. The Father — described by the cosmic predicates *for whom are all things, and through whom are all things* — found it *fitting* (*eprepō*, to be appropriate, to befit one's character) to bring many sons to glory by *perfecting* the *archēgos* of their salvation through sufferings. Each word repays attention.\n\n*Fitting* is not necessity in the sense of external constraint but appropriateness — the suffering-path of the Son matches the character of the Father. *Many sons* (*pollous huious*) is the chapter's first use of son-language for believers; it picks up the language of v. 7 (man crowned) and gives it eschatological extension. The destination is *doxa* (glory) — the same glory with which Jesus is already crowned in v. 9. *Archēgos* is a remarkably rich term: in classical Greek it can mean founder, originator, prince, captain, trailblazer. The translation 'pioneer' captures the dynamic: He goes first along the path the many sons must travel. He is not merely the cause of their salvation; He is the file-leader of the procession.\n\n*Teleiōsai* (to perfect) requires careful handling. It does not mean moral improvement — the Son needed none. In Hebrews it is vocational completion: He was made *fit for His office* by the actual undergoing of the human ordeal. The same root will return at 5:8-9 (He learned obedience by the things which He suffered; having been made perfect, He became the source of eternal salvation) and 7:28 (the Son perfected forever). The cumulative force is that Christ's high-priestly qualification required not just His deity but His tested humanity.\n\nVerses 11-13 ground the brotherhood with a triad of OT quotations. The first premise (v. 11): *both He who sanctifies and those who are sanctified are all from one* (*ex henos pantes*). The 'one' is most naturally read as the Father (cf. 1:6, 13; the Father has been the chapter's repeated reference), though some readers take it as 'one humanity' or 'one Adam.' Either way, the point is shared origin grounding shared kinship. *Therefore He is not ashamed* (*ouk epaischynomai*, the same construction that will reappear at 11:16 of God's relation to the patriarchs) *to call them brethren*.\n\nThree citations confirm the brotherhood. Psalm 22:22 (v. 12) is from the great suffering psalm whose opening cry Christ took on the cross (Matthew 27:46); its second half is the resurrection-and-victory section, in which the Sufferer proclaims God's name to His brethren and sings the Father's praise *in the congregation* (*ekklēsia*). The risen Christ thus stands among His brothers as the lead worshiper. Isaiah 8:17 (v. 13a) gives Christ as the model of trust — *I will put My trust in Him* — depicting the incarnate Son as the perfect believer. Isaiah 8:18 (v. 13b) — *Behold, I and the children whom God has given Me* — completes the picture: the Son receives His brothers as a gift from the Father, language that resonates with John 6:37-39 and 17:6-9.\n\nNotice the architecture: from *sons* (v. 10) to *brothers* (v. 11) to *children* (v. 13). The relational vocabulary gathers density precisely as the author prepares to argue, in vv. 14-18, that this family-relation required the incarnation.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Archēgos* appears four times in the NT (Acts 3:15; 5:31; Hebrews 2:10; 12:2). In Hebrews 12:2 He is *archēgos and perfecter (teleiōtēs) of faith* — the same root cluster as 2:10. *Teleioō* in Hebrews is consistently vocational/positional, not moral. *Ek henos* (from one) is deliberately ambiguous — the author wants the reader to feel both the shared Father and the shared humanity."
