        "number": 4,
        "title": "Incarnation as conquest — the destruction of death and the devil",
        "range": "2:14-16",
        "excerpt": "Therefore, since the children share in flesh and blood, He Himself likewise also partook of the same, that through death He might render powerless him who had the power of death, that is, the devil.",
        "body": "*Therefore* (*epei oun*) draws the consequence of the brotherhood established in vv. 11-13. The brotherhood was not symbolic. Because the children share *haima kai sarx* — flesh and blood, the standard Jewish idiom for ordinary human existence — He Himself *likewise also partook* (*paraplēsiōs metechō*) of the same. The vocabulary is precise. *Koinōneō* (share) in the first half of v. 14 is what the children have done by birth — they were born flesh-and-blood. *Metechō* (partook of) in the second half is what the Son did — He, who was not by nature flesh-and-blood, took it to Himself. The slight difference of verbs guards both the reality of the incarnation and the difference between the Son's eternal nature and His assumed humanity.\n\nThe purpose-clause is the chapter's most dramatic statement of the cross's victory: *that through death He might render powerless him who had the power of death, that is, the devil*. *Katargeō* (render powerless, abolish, deactivate) is a Pauline favorite (1 Corinthians 15:24-26; 2 Timothy 1:10), and Hebrews uses it here for the satanic stronghold of death. The strategic genius of the cross is captured in the phrase *through death*: the devil's weapon was death; Christ took death into Himself and thereby disarmed the wielder. This is what the Eastern church has called the *Christus Victor* dimension of the atonement — not in competition with penal substitution (which v. 17 will introduce) but as one of its effects. By bearing sin's penalty, Christ removed the legal grounds on which the devil exercised the power of death (cf. Colossians 2:13-15).\n\nVerse 15 names the pastoral payoff: *and might free those who through fear of death were subject to slavery all their lives*. *Apallassō* (free, deliver) is a strong verb of release. *Phobos thanatou* (fear of death) is the chapter's diagnosis of unredeemed human existence — not death itself merely, but the slavery the *fear* of death imposes. Pre-Christian humanity is pictured as living its entire span under a tyranny: every choice colored by mortality, every decision haunted by the end. Christ's death does not abolish biological death (yet), but it severs the chain of fear. The believer can now look at death and say with Paul, *to die is gain* (Philippians 1:21).\n\nVerse 16 sharpens the particularity: *for assuredly He does not give help to angels* (*epilambanetai*, lay hold of, take by the hand), *but He gives help to the descendant of Abraham*. The verb pictures rescue: the Son reaches down and takes hold not of angelic beings but of the Abrahamic seed. *Sperma Abraam* is covenantal — those who belong to the line of promise, fulfilled in believing Jew and Gentile alike (Galatians 3:7, 29). The contrast with angels closes the chapter's frame: the warning began with the angelic mediation of Sinai (v. 2); the consolation ends with the unequivocal statement that Christ's saving help is not for angels.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Haima kai sarx* (blood and flesh) — the Greek order is the reverse of English idiom. *Paraplēsiōs* (likewise, similarly) does not weaken the incarnation but emphasizes its closeness. *Katargeō* — literally to render *argos* (idle, inactive) — is not annihilation but deactivation; the devil still exists but his death-power is broken. *Epilambanomai* — the same verb Jesus uses of taking Peter by the hand on the water (Matthew 14:31)."
